# Git Discipline

Before starting any work, always pull the latest changes:

```
git pull
```

After any file edit (code changes, new files, config updates, etc.), stage, commit, and push:

```
git add -A
git commit -m "<concise description of the change>"
git push
```

This applies to every editing session — never leave uncommitted or unpushed work.

# IAS Typhon Cluster Workflow

## Project context

This project simulates 3-body gravitational scattering of stars off a binary black hole.
The C++ code uses OpenMP for parallelisation and runs on the IAS "typhon" SLURM cluster
(96 cores per node). Source files live in:

    3-body/C++/

SLURM job scripts live in:

    3-body/slurm/

## The cluster helper script

All cluster operations go through `cluster.sh` in the C++ source directory.
Always `cd` into that directory before calling it:

```
cd 3-body/C++
```

### Available commands

| Command | What it does |
|---|---|
| `./cluster.sh deploy <files...>` | Upload files to the cluster |
| `./cluster.sh compile <file.cpp> [output]` | Compile on the cluster (default output: `scattering`) |
| `./cluster.sh submit <slurm_file>` | Submit a SLURM job |
| `./cluster.sh run <file.cpp> [opts] -- <args...>` | **Full pipeline**: deploy + compile + generate SLURM + submit |
| `./cluster.sh sweep <file.cpp> <slurm_file>` | Deploy + compile + submit an array job |
| `./cluster.sh status` | Show the job queue |
| `./cluster.sh cancel <job_id\|all>` | Cancel a job (or all jobs) |
| `./cluster.sh fetch [pattern] [--dest dir]` | Download results (default: `*.txt` + `*.bin` + `harmonics_*` to `./results/`) |
| `./cluster.sh logs <job_id>` | Show stdout/stderr for a job |
| `./cluster.sh clean` | Remove `*.out` and `*.err` on the cluster |
| `./cluster.sh ls [subdir]` | List remote files |
| `./cluster.sh wait <job_id>` | Poll until a job finishes |

### The `run` command in detail

Options **before** `--` control the SLURM job:
- `--time HH:MM:SS` (default `12:00:00`)
- `--cpus N` (default `96`)
- `--output NAME` (default `scattering`)

Everything **after** `--` is passed verbatim to the compiled executable.

### The `sweep` command

Since SLURM scripts now live in `3-body/slurm/` (a sibling of `3-body/C++/`),
reference them with a relative path from the C++ directory:

```
./cluster.sh sweep main.cpp ../slurm/sweep-scattering.slurm
```

## Known C++ programs and their parameters

| File | Arguments (positional) |
|---|---|
| `main.cpp` | `q e` |
| `main_hvs.cpp` | `q e` |
| `main-print-trajectory.cpp` | `q e` |
| `main-3D-velocity.cpp` | `q e [N_v] [N] [l_max]` |

When the user specifies named parameters like `q=0.3 e=0.7 N_v=2000`, extract the values
and pass them **in the positional order** shown above after the `--` separator.

If you encounter a new C++ file you haven't seen before, read its `main()` function to
determine what arguments it expects, then pass them in the correct order.

## Mapping natural language to commands

| User says (examples) | You run |
|---|---|
| "run main-3D-velocity with q=0.3, e=0.7, N_v=2000" | `./cluster.sh run main-3D-velocity.cpp -- 0.3 0.7 2000` |
| "run main.cpp with q=0.2 e=0.6, give it 6 hours" | `./cluster.sh run main.cpp --time 06:00:00 -- 0.2 0.6` |
| "launch the sweep" | `./cluster.sh sweep <file.cpp> ../slurm/sweep-scattering.slurm` (ask which file if unclear) |
| "check my jobs" / "job status" | `./cluster.sh status` |
| "get the results" / "fetch results" | `./cluster.sh fetch` |
| "clean up the cluster" | `./cluster.sh clean` |
| "cancel job 12345" | `./cluster.sh cancel 12345` |
| "cancel everything" | `./cluster.sh cancel all` |
| "show logs for job 12345" | `./cluster.sh logs 12345` |
| "what's on the cluster?" | `./cluster.sh ls` |

If the user says "deploy" or "upload" without asking to run, use `deploy` only.
If they say "compile" without asking to run, use `deploy` then `compile`.

## Full-lifecycle workflow

When the user asks to **run code AND get results back** (e.g. "run X and get me the
results"), follow this full lifecycle:

1. Run `./cluster.sh run <file> [opts] -- <args>` to deploy, compile, and submit.
2. Parse the job ID from the sbatch output (e.g. "Submitted batch job 9424310").
3. **Check the requested walltime:**
   - **Short jobs (--time <= 01:00:00):** Tell the user you will monitor the job.
     Poll `./cluster.sh status` every 2-3 minutes. When the job disappears from the
     queue, run `./cluster.sh fetch` and `./cluster.sh clean`, then report back.
   - **Long jobs (--time > 01:00:00):** Tell the user: "Job XXXX submitted with a
     Y-hour walltime. When you're ready, ask me to check status or fetch results."
     Do NOT attempt to poll for hours — the user may close Cursor or sleep their laptop.
4. When fetching results after a long job, always also clean up:
   `./cluster.sh fetch && ./cluster.sh clean`

## Important notes

- The cluster job runs independently on SLURM. Closing Cursor or sleeping the laptop
  does NOT affect the job. The user can always come back and ask for status or results.
- All SSH goes through the `typhon-login1` host alias (ProxyJump configured in ~/.ssh/config).
- The compile command on the cluster is: `g++ -std=c++17 -fopenmp -O3 -march=native`
- Always use `required_permissions: ["full_network"]` (or `["all"]`) when calling
  `cluster.sh`, since it needs SSH/rsync access to the cluster.
